sentences: Clara Gottschalk was born in 1837 in New Orleans, Louisiana, one of the seven children of London-born Edward Gottschalk and Aimée (née Bruslé).
In 1847, Aimée left her husband and moved with six of the children to Paris, France, where Louis Moreau was already studying music.
The youngest brother, Louis Gaston Gottschalk (1845–1912), was an eminent opera singer and vocal teacher.
In 1880, Clara Gottschalk married Dr. Robert E. Peterson in Philadelphia.
section: == Marriage and Notes of a Pianist ==

sentences: In 1881, she published a collection of Louis Moreau's travel notes and diaries, entitled Notes of a Pianist, with 'a long biographical preface gathering many testimonials and reviews from newspapers (all elogious)'.
section: == Marriage and Notes of a Pianist ==

sentences: In 1902, Clara published Creole Songs from New Orleans in the Negro Dialect.
Clara Gottschalk Peterson died at her home in Asbury Park, New Jersey on 25 July 1910.
Clara Gottschalk Peterson (1837-1910) was an American pianist, composer, and editor.

The New York Times noted that her house had been:for many years the gathering place of Asbury Park's musicians, and even during the past Winter, despite her failing health, she gave musicales at which she played her brother's compositions.
She was survived by two step-children and her sister, Celestine Gottschalk, with whom she had lived for a number of years.
